==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Travesty
<hw>Trav"es*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>travesti</ets>, p. p. of <ets>travestir</ets> to disguise, to
travesty, It. <ets>travestire</ets>, fr. L. <ets>trans</ets> across,
over + <ets>vestire</ets> to dress, clothe. See <er>Vest</er>.]</ety>
<def>Disguised by dress so as to be ridiculous; travestied; -- applied
to a book or shorter composition.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Travesty</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Travesty
<hw>Trav"es*ty</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Travesties</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>A burlesque translation
or imitation of a work.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The second edition is not a recast, but absolutely a
<qex>travesty</qex> of the first.</q> <rj><qau>De
Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Travesty</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Travesty
<hw>Trav"es*ty</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Travestied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Travesting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To translate, imitate, or
represent, so as to render ridiculous or ludicrous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I see poor Lucan <qex>travestied</qex>, not appareled in his Roman
toga, but under the cruel shears of an English tailor.</q>
<rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

